<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06113153 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06113153 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  PAST; OREGON; BANK; ROBBERY; VICTIM; SUPPORT; GROUP; PROGRAM  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  The armed robber, his face obscured by a ski mask, visits the teller in herdreams night after night.;    At work at the bank, if anyone resembling thegunman walks in, her palms sweat and she's gripped by nausea.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  General News  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  'THIS IS A SUPPORT GROUP': ROBBED BANK TELLERSGET HELP  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     She just can't shake the fear he may return.;    Such reactions are typicalof those suffered by tellers who work for the more than 6,000 U.S. banks heldup every year, says Pamela Powers, who has set up a special support group inPortland for such victims.;    Powers, a victim-witness specialist with theU.S. attorney's office who works with bank robbery cases, says the victims'assistance program is the first in the country for employees of financialinstitutions.;    Since the program's inception last year, dozens of victimshave participated in its free weekly group therapy sessions. Powers saidseveral cities, including Portland, Maine, have expressed interest indeveloping such a program.;    The program here began with a $12,000 grantfrom Oregon's Financial Institutions Security Task Force, representing banks,savings and loans and credit unions. A handful of people attend each session.;   &quot;Being a victim teller is an extremely difficult situation,&quot; said taskforce chairman, Bob Burns, manager of the Multco Credit Union. &quot;I've been avictim twice from gun robberies.;    &quot;In the last one, a fellow came in and hewas obviously going to rob us. He pulled a gun on me, chambered a shell andhad me clean out three teller drawers.&quot;;    He said the robbery upset him somuch he couldn't properly describe the gunman to police.;    The program helpsvictims find out the problems they suffer in the crime's aftermath are notunique to them. Robbery victims may hyperventilate or have difficultysleeping, stomach distress, fatigue and a host of emotional and behavioralproblems. Such symptoms can persist a long time.;    &quot;It doesn't have to besomeone who was just robbed,&quot; Powers said. &quot;We're getting people who wererobbed 10 years ago and are having problems dealing with the robbery.&quot;;   Most armed robbers make off with less than $2,000 and never use their weapons,but the crime can still leave the victims debilitated and traumatized.;    In&quot;A Guide to Surviving a Robbery,&quot; Powers wrote that recovery for victimsdepends on such factors as the nature of the crime and their treatment by lawenforcement, co-workers, family and friends.;    Patricia Lounsbury, a tellerat the ACU Credit Union in Fenton, Mo., said the two men who robbed heremployer also stole her peace of mind.;    &quot;It will never go away, you know,&quot;she said in a documentary prepared by the Cumis Insurance Society in Madison,Wis. &quot;You can talk to people about it and try to get help but you will alwaysbe afraid.;    &quot;Those two people just changed my whole life. Before I wouldnever be afraid of anything.&quot;  </TEXT><BYLINE>  RICHARD GREEN, Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Portland, Ore.  </CITY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910422  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Monday  </DAY><MONTH>  April  </MONTH><PG.COL>  2F  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  473  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Monday April 22, 199100113153,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>